<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="5"><b>The American way of war crimes</b></font><p>
<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">June 9, 2006 | Pages 6 and 7</font><p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">JOE ALLEN is the son and nephew of Marines--his uncle, a veteran of the Vietnam War, died from cancer as a result of his exposure to the herbicide Agent Orange. Joe's articles on the history of the Vietnam War have appeared in the <i>International Socialist Review. </i>Here, he explains why the massacres of civilians in Iraq are part of a long and bloody record of U.S. war crimes.<p>
<p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="1">- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -</font></p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">ON MAY 24, Gen. Michael Hagee, Commandant of the United States Marine Corps, made a quickly arranged flight to Iraq to deal with the growing political fallout from a series of criminal investigations into the murder of Iraqi civilians by U.S. Marines.<p>

<table width="264" align="right" border="0"><tr><td>
